From: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
Date: Sat, 23 May 2026 02:30:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: ethernet: qcom: ppe: edma: leak skb on ndev-null drop

The IPQ5332 EDMA occasionally emits descriptors whose buffer the HW
is still actively DMA-ing into (PORTID-valid, src_port_num=1, real
frame data — but the netdev for port 1 isn't yet registered at
that point in boot). The previous behaviour `dev_kfree_skb_any(skb)`
in `edma_rx_get_src_dev`'s failure path freed the skb while the
slab page was still hot under HW writes; when the slab allocator
later recycled that page, integrity checks blew up with a
`__slab_free` BUG at `edma_rx_napi_poll+0x3cc` (also seen at
+0x3a0 with the cons_idx-keyed lookup variant — same bug, same
trigger).

Hardening: don't free the skb in the ndev-null drop path. Let it
leak; the next call to `edma_rx_alloc_buffer_list` will refill
the RXFILL slot with a fresh skb. The leaked one becomes
unreachable but doesn't corrupt the slab.

This is a temporary trade-off — once eth0's netdev is registered
before the EDMA starts pumping RX (via correct DSA ordering, or
by holding RX disabled until the netdev exists), this branch
should not be hit during normal operation. Boot-time spurious
frames hit this on the way to a functional steady state.

Signed-off-by: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/qualcomm/ppe/edma_rx.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/qualcomm/ppe/edma_rx.c
@@ -516,7 +516,15 @@ static int edma_rx_reap(struct edma_rxdesc_ring *rxdesc_ring, int budget)
 		if (likely(!(rxdesc_ring->head))) {
 			ndev = edma_rx_get_src_dev(rxdesc_stats, rxdesc_pri, skb);
 			if (unlikely(!ndev)) {
-				dev_kfree_skb_any(skb);
+				/* Hardening: don't free here. The IPQ5332
+				 * EDMA hands us valid-looking descriptors
+				 * whose backing buffer the HW is still
+				 * DMA-ing into; freeing the skb causes
+				 * slab corruption when the page is
+				 * recycled. Leak instead.
+				 */
+				if (net_ratelimit())
+					pr_warn_once("ndev-null drop: leaking skb (HW DMA still hot)\n");
 				goto next_rx_desc;
 			}

